{"id":"1708.08463","submitter":"Johannes Tiedau","authors":"Johannes Tiedau, Valery S. Shchesnovich, Dmitri Mogilevtsev, Vahid\n  Ansari, Georg Harder, Tim Bartley, Natalia Korolkova and Christine Silberhorn","title":"Trading quantum states for temporal profiles: tomography by the overlap","comments":"11 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1367-2630/aaad8a","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quantum states and the modes of the optical field they occupy are\nintrinsically connected. Here, we show that one can trade the knowledge of a\nquantum state to gain information about the underlying mode structure and, vice\nversa, the knowledge about the modal shape allows one to perform a complete\ntomography of the quantum state. Our scheme can be executed experimentally\nusing the interference between the signal and probe states on an unbalanced\nbeam splitter with a single on/off-type detector. By changing the temporal\noverlap between the signal and the probe, the imperfect interference is turned\ninto a powerful tool to extract the information about the signal mode\nstructure. A single on/off detector is already sufficient to collect the\nnecessary measurement data for the reconstruction of the diagonal part of the\ndensity matrix of an arbitrary multi-mode signal. Moreover, we experimentally\ndemonstrate the feasibility of our scheme with just one control parameter --\nthe time-delay of a coherent probe field.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 28 Aug 2017 18:00:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-04-04"}
